---
title: Setup & Configure
description: Installation and configuration instructions for MCP
---
This guide will walk you through the process of setting up and configuring MCP module for your Drupal site.

## Install the fresh Drupal CMS (optional)

If you don't have an existing Drupal site, you can install a fresh one using DDEV.

This is from the [Drupal CMS official documentation](https://new.drupal.org/docs/drupal-cms/get-started/install-drupal-cms/install-drupal-cms-locally-with-ddev).

```bash
mkdir my-drupal-site && cd my-drupal-site
ddev config --project-type=drupal11 --docroot=web
ddev start
ddev composer create drupal/cms
``` 

## Install and enable the MCP Module

```bash
ddev composer require 'drupal/mcp:^1.0'
ddev drush en mcp -y
```

## Enable Plugins

MCP module supports a plugin-based architecture that allows developers to extend its functionality. The module itself implements the MCP protocol itself and acts as a foundation, but the actual actions and resources that are being exposed to the outside world, is controlled by the plugins. You can also [create your custom plugin](/en/developers/create-plugin/).

MCP module comes with two submodules which define the useful plugins - `mcp_extra` which exposes AI modules function calling actions, and `mcp_dev_tools` which basically exposes drush to LLMs. Enabling both of them is very useful in effectively using MCP. *Note that in order extra module to expose AI functions, you need to install and enable [Drupal AI module](https://drupal.org/project/ai).*

```bash
ddev drush en mcp_extra
ddev drush en mcp_dev_tools
```

## Configure

After this, you should be able to see the MCP module's configuration under the Web Services and access it at `/admin/config/mcp`.

On the module configuration page, you enable the auth and control how authentification is done (token based or credentials) and enable or disable the plugins mentioned above and configure their settings for each of them.
